==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Organize
<hw>Or"gan*ize</hw> <pr>(⟦ocir⟧r"g⟦ait⟧n*⟦imac⟧z)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Organized</conjf>
<pr>(⟦ocir⟧r"g⟦ait⟧n*⟦imac⟧zd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Organizing</conjf>
<pr>(⟦ocir⟧r"g⟦ait⟧n*⟦imac⟧*z⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>organiser</ets>, Gr. <grk>'organi`zein</grk>. See
<er>Organ</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>To furnish
with organs; to give an organic structure to; to endow with capacity for
the functions of life; <as>as, an <ex>organized</ex> being;
<ex>organized</ex> matter</as>; -- in this sense used chiefly in the
past participle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These nobler faculties of the mind, matter <qex>organized</qex>
could never produce.</q> <rj><qau>Ray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To arrange or constitute in parts, each having a
special function, act, office, or relation; to systematize; to get into
working order; -- applied to products of the human intellect, or to
human institutions and undertakings, as a science, a government, an
army, a war, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This original and supreme will <qex>organizes</qex> the
government.</q> <rj><qau>Cranch.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To sing in parts; <as>as, to
<ex>organize</ex> an anthem</as>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Busby.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>organized</ent>⟦br⟧
